## **Q2 Iteration 3 Optimization Summary**

### **Performance Baseline**
- **Iteration 1 baseline**: 95.61 ms
- **Iteration 2 (failed)**: 100.49 ms (regressed, rolled back)
- **Target**: Beat 95.61 ms baseline and close gap to DuckDB (63 ms)
- **Gap to best**: 1.5x slower than DuckDB

### **Bottleneck Analysis**
The original profiling data showed:
1. **`subquery_and_index`: 37.92 ms (39.6%)** — Parallel loop scanning 8M partsupp rows with critical section bottleneck
2. **`load_dicts`: 30.48 ms (31.9%)** — Dictionary loading happening AFTER main computation
3. **Other operations**: ~26.8 ms combined

### **Three Major Optimizations Implemented**

#### **1. Eliminate Critical Section Bottleneck in Subquery Phase (-~10-15ms expected)**
**Problem**: The original code used `#pragma omp critical(min_update)` when updating minimum supply costs across 8M partsupp rows. This serializes updates across threads, creating severe contention on high core counts (64 cores).

**Solution**: Switched to **thread-local aggregation** for minimum costs:
- Each thread maintains its own hash map of `{partkey → min_cost}` (local_min_costs[tid])
- No synchronization during the hot loop
- After parallel phase, merge thread-local mins sequentially in O(num_threads × qualified_parts) time
- Expected improvement: **10-15ms** (eliminates lock contention entirely)

**Code changes**:
```cpp
// OLD: #pragma omp critical(min_update) { ... update global min ... }
// NEW: Thread-local map, no locking during parallel phase
int tid = omp_get_thread_num();
auto& local_min_map = local_min_costs[tid];
if (sc < local_min_map[pk]) local_min_map[pk] = sc;
```

#### **2. Early Dictionary Loading - Hide I/O Latency (-~8-12ms expected)**
**Problem**: Dictionaries were loaded AFTER the subquery/index phase (30.48 ms), forcing sequential execution of I/O and computation. High-latency I/O (file reads) blocks the next phase.

**Solution**: Move all dictionary loading to execute in **parallel sections BEFORE** the main query logic starts:
- 8 parallel sections loading region, nation, supplier (4 columns), and part dictionaries
- Overlaps I/O latency with each other
- Main query phases can proceed immediately after
- Expected improvement: **8-12ms** (reduced stalling on I/O)

**Code changes**:
```cpp
// Load all 8 dictionaries in parallel sections at startup
#pragma omp parallel sections {
    #pragma omp section region_name_dict = load_dictionary(...);
    #pragma omp section nation_name_dict = load_dictionary(...);
    #pragma omp section supp_name_dict = load_dictionary(...);
    // ... etc for all dictionaries
}
// Now main query starts immediately after, without I/O stalls
```

#### **3. Parallelize and Optimize Filter Operations (-~5-8ms expected)**
**Problem**: 
- Part filtering (2M rows, 9.6 ms) and supplier filtering (100K rows, 5.36 ms) were sequential
- Supplier filtering used `std::unordered_set` for nation lookup (25 nations — tiny domain)

**Optimizations**:
a) **Parallel part filtering with thread-local results** (no critical section)
   - Split 2M rows across threads, each thread populates its own vector of qualified partkey indices
   - Merge results after parallel phase
   - Replace `unordered_set<int32_t>` lookup with simple `vector<bool>` (O(1), better cache)
   - Expected: ~2-3ms savings

b) **Parallel supplier filtering with direct array indexing**
   - Replace `unordered_set<int32_t>` for 25 nations with `vector<bool>[25]`
   - Direct indexing: `is_qualified_nation[nationkey]` vs hash table lookup
   - Parallelize across 100K rows
   - Expected: ~2-3ms savings

c) **Branch prediction optimization**
   - Check `part_sizes[i] == 15` FIRST (more selective on 2M rows)
   - Then check type (avoids wasted type lookups on wrong sizes)
   - Reduces branch mispredicts on tight filtering loop

**Code changes**:
```cpp
// OLD: std::unordered_set<int32_t> qualified_nation_set(...)
//      for (uint32_t i = 0; i < 100000; i++)
//          if (qualified_nation_set.count(supp_nationkeys[i])) ...

// NEW: Thread-local collection + direct array lookup
std::vector<bool> is_qualified_nation(25, false);
for (int32_t n : qualified_nations) is_qualified_nation[n] = true;
#pragma omp parallel for schedule(dynamic, 10000)
for (uint32_t i = 0; i < 100000; i++)
    if (supp_nationkeys[i] < 25 && is_qualified_nation[supp_nationkeys[i]]) ...
```

